Thank you for coming.

00:38:37.355 --> 00:38:39.390
PJ VOGT: Yeah, thank you.

00:38:39.390 --> 00:38:43.040
AUDIENCE: So you host
a successful podcast

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:44.880
on a growing network.

00:38:44.880 --> 00:38:48.840
What's become easier for you
to do as Gimlet has grown

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:52.590
and your show remains
successful and popular?

00:38:52.590 --> 00:38:55.930
And what's become
harder for you to do?

00:38:55.930 --> 00:38:57.540
PJ VOGT: Well, I
mean, just resources,

00:38:57.540 --> 00:39:01.780
in terms of traveling to do
a story, people understanding

00:39:01.780 --> 00:39:04.080
that we're a thing that's
worth an hour of their time

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:06.132
if we want to interview them.

00:39:06.132 --> 00:39:07.590
We have more people,
which means we

00:39:07.590 --> 00:39:10.710
can try weirder stuff, because
things can fail and that's OK,

00:39:10.710 --> 00:39:14.970
which really wasn't
true in the beginning.

00:39:14.970 --> 00:39:19.640
I've lately been feeling
that feeling of--

00:39:19.640 --> 00:39:21.470
I keep thinking
about "The Simpsons"

00:39:21.470 --> 00:39:24.552
and how, if you're around long
enough, how often you come up

00:39:24.552 --> 00:39:26.760
with what you think is a
good idea, then you're like,

00:39:26.760 --> 00:39:27.940
oh, we did that.

00:39:27.940 --> 00:39:31.244
Like, we've had that question.

00:39:31.244 --> 00:39:33.660
I feel we're lucky that we're
covering the internet, which

00:39:33.660 --> 00:39:35.820
is not a stable, boring place.

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:38.560
But I've felt that
anxiety, lately, more.

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:40.230
ALEX GOLDMAN: Me, too.

00:39:40.230 --> 00:39:42.810
Yeah, we're almost
100 episodes in.

00:39:42.810 --> 00:39:46.110
And every once in
a while, we'll have

00:39:46.110 --> 00:39:49.540
a really fallow
period and PJ will

00:39:49.540 --> 00:39:51.030
be like, we're out of stories.

00:39:51.030 --> 00:39:52.664
And then a month
later, he'll be like,

00:39:52.664 --> 00:39:54.330
we're never going to
run out of stories.

00:39:54.330 --> 00:39:56.246
PJ VOGT: Yeah, we're out
of stories right now.

00:39:56.246 --> 00:39:58.710
So that's the prism that
I'm answering that question

00:39:58.710 --> 00:40:00.510
through.

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:03.140
I honestly think I won't
have an idea again.

00:40:03.140 --> 00:40:05.160
We'll see.

00:40:05.160 --> 00:40:06.060
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:08.000
PJ VOGT: Thanks.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:09.880
AUDIENCE: So thanks for coming.

00:40:09.880 --> 00:40:11.670
I did want to say,
Sruthi Pinnamaneni

00:40:11.670 --> 00:40:13.070
is amazing and awesome.

00:40:13.070 --> 00:40:13.340
ALEX GOLDMAN: Yes.

00:40:13.340 --> 00:40:14.215
PJ VOGT: Yes, she is.

00:40:14.215 --> 00:40:16.170
AUDIENCE: Too bad
she's not here.

00:40:16.170 --> 00:40:20.970
And what I wanted to ask you is,
so since you started the show,

00:40:20.970 --> 00:40:23.610
it seems like memes
have taken on a kind

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:27.000
of political significance
and a relevance

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.320
that they didn't
necessarily have before.

00:40:29.320 --> 00:40:33.070
They've become more powerful,
more disturbing in many ways.

00:40:33.070 --> 00:40:37.680
And I'm wondering, how has
that changed how you approach

00:40:37.680 --> 00:40:39.936
a segment like "Yes Yes No"?

00:40:39.936 --> 00:40:42.060
PJ VOGT: Yeah, we were
talking about this recently.

00:40:42.060 --> 00:40:43.740
I mean, weirdly,
in some ways, it

00:40:43.740 --> 00:40:45.360
makes that segment
work less well,

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:49.110
only because the sort of
toxic, weird, dark stuff

00:40:49.110 --> 00:40:51.720
that was on the internet is
now so much in the culture

00:40:51.720 --> 00:40:54.510
that a lot of these memes
just aren't obscure.

00:40:54.510 --> 00:40:57.656
It makes it more fun when
it works, because it just

00:40:57.656 --> 00:41:00.030
feels like internet culture
is culture, rather than being

00:41:00.030 --> 00:41:00.960
something to the side.

00:41:00.960 --> 00:41:03.130
And so even though it's
not fun to be talking

00:41:03.130 --> 00:41:07.470
about the wacky origins
of some neo-Nazi in-joke,

00:41:07.470 --> 00:41:12.350
from a reporting standpoint, or
from a journalistic standpoint,

00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:18.990
it matters now, or sometimes it
matters, and that feels good.

00:41:18.990 --> 00:41:21.160
It feels like, oh,
it's actually--

00:41:21.160 --> 00:41:24.420
there's a utility to explaining
this, instead of just

00:41:24.420 --> 00:41:26.239
celebrating something
for being obscure.

00:41:26.239 --> 00:41:27.530
ALEX GOLDMAN: I agree with him.

