We write script in between it
to explain and contextualize

00:41:52.766 --> 00:41:53.810
what they say.

00:41:53.810 --> 00:41:58.260
Our stories tend to
be five to 30 minutes.

00:41:58.260 --> 00:42:00.160
We don't have to worry about--

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:03.500
like, we did a story that was
about experimenting with LSD.

00:42:03.500 --> 00:42:05.915
We couldn't have done
that on the radio.

00:42:05.915 --> 00:42:07.040
ALEX GOLDMAN: We can swear.

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:08.170
PJ VOGT: We can swear.

00:42:08.170 --> 00:42:09.945
ALEX GOLDMAN: We don't have
to worry about the clock.

00:42:09.945 --> 00:42:12.278
Things can be as long or as
short as we want them to be.

00:42:12.278 --> 00:42:14.860
PJ VOGT: Which is so oppressive
and constant in radio.

00:42:14.860 --> 00:42:16.420
Like, where really,
you're like, this

00:42:16.420 --> 00:42:17.800
has to be 12 and a half minutes.

00:42:17.800 --> 00:42:19.744
And if there's 15
interesting minutes,

00:42:19.744 --> 00:42:21.160
they're going to
have to come out.

00:42:21.160 --> 00:42:22.899
And if there's seven
interesting minutes,

00:42:22.899 --> 00:42:24.190
you're going to have to pad it.

00:42:24.190 --> 00:42:28.330
That's a very real,
ceaseless problem in radio,

00:42:28.330 --> 00:42:29.500
that we just don't--

00:42:29.500 --> 00:42:31.000
the thing we have
to deal with is

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.670
we need a story that can
carry over an ad break.

00:42:33.670 --> 00:42:35.290
That's the hardest.

00:42:35.290 --> 00:42:38.212
ALEX GOLDMAN: And a lot of
times, that is a real problem.

00:42:38.212 --> 00:42:39.670
PJ VOGT: Yeah, but
it's not-- like,

00:42:39.670 --> 00:42:41.570
that's the one thing
that it gives you.

00:42:41.570 --> 00:42:44.520
No, podcasting is great.

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:46.300
Also, the people that
listen to the show

00:42:46.300 --> 00:42:48.175
are more likely to have
found it because they

00:42:48.175 --> 00:42:50.330
want to hear it, versus
I was listening to NPR

00:42:50.330 --> 00:42:52.660
and then this crap
came on, which

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:55.156
is like, it forces you to--

00:42:55.156 --> 00:42:57.280
on podcasting, you can
trust that your audience has

00:42:57.280 --> 00:42:59.360
heard you before and
that they're game.

00:42:59.360 --> 00:43:01.036
ALEX GOLDMAN: Right.

00:43:01.036 --> 00:43:01.980
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:43:01.980 --> 00:43:03.780
PJ VOGT: Thank you.

00:43:03.780 --> 00:43:05.320
AUDIENCE: So "This
American Life"

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:06.704
was probably the
first radio show

00:43:06.704 --> 00:43:08.120
that I listened
to that would just

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:10.255
tell stories that were
so compelling that I'd

00:43:10.255 --> 00:43:12.880
have to sit in my car when I got
into my driveway after school,

00:43:12.880 --> 00:43:15.310
just to finish
listening to them.

00:43:15.310 --> 00:43:17.620
And I was wondering, having
sort of started there

00:43:17.620 --> 00:43:21.102
as an intern, PJ, to what
extent did your experience

00:43:21.102 --> 00:43:22.810
there influence the
way that you approach

00:43:22.810 --> 00:43:24.019
a story for "Reply All"?

00:43:24.019 --> 00:43:25.560
Because I definitely
kind of get some

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:27.595
of the same magic feelings.

00:43:27.595 --> 00:43:28.720
PJ VOGT: Well, thank you.

00:43:28.720 --> 00:43:32.860
I mean, for me, that
place is church.

00:43:32.860 --> 00:43:37.430
Like, the values that they have,
and the craft that they have,

00:43:37.430 --> 00:43:41.410
it's a standard that I think
about pretty constantly.

00:43:41.410 --> 00:43:43.241
I think that there
is a mode of story

00:43:43.241 --> 00:43:44.740
that I'll report
on "Reply All" that

00:43:44.740 --> 00:43:50.300
feels like me doing my best to
do an homage to what they do.

00:43:50.300 --> 00:43:54.880
Like, the Brinkley story
we just did, it's written--

00:43:54.880 --> 00:43:57.130
it doesn't rely on Alex
and I's conversation.

00:43:57.130 --> 00:44:00.540
Those stories feel
more to their thing.

00:44:00.540 --> 00:44:04.615
Tim, who is our editor and
executive producer, just

00:44:04.615 --> 00:44:07.484
the brilliant person
on staff, he's

00:44:07.484 --> 00:44:08.650
always pushing us out of it.

00:44:08.650 --> 00:44:11.800
He's always pushing for
more of me and Alex.

00:44:11.800 --> 00:44:13.870
Or he's like, stop
writing so much.

00:44:13.870 --> 00:44:14.980
He hates writing.

00:44:14.980 --> 00:44:16.790
I love writing.

00:44:16.790 --> 00:44:18.106
But I still think--

00:44:18.106 --> 00:44:19.480
I still just listen
to that show,

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:21.645
and I'm just like, how
do you guys do this?

00:44:21.645 --> 00:44:22.780
It's so crazy.

00:44:22.780 --> 00:44:25.840
They're so good, and they
do so many different things,

00:44:25.840 --> 00:44:27.100
and they do them so well.

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:29.290
It's not fair.

00:44:29.290 --> 00:44:29.790
Yeah.

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:35.120
AUDIENCE: Hey, guys.

00:44:35.120 --> 00:44:39.020
So being at a technology
company, and more specifically,

00:44:39.020 --> 00:44:41.570
a technology company
that has its hands

00:44:41.570 --> 00:44:44.420
pretty deeply into
advertising, it's hard for me

00:44:44.420 --> 00:44:47.000
not to look at podcasting
through kind of a technology

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:48.080
lens.

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:49.890
And a lot of times,
I look at podcasts,

00:44:49.890 --> 00:44:52.610
and I think about how
primitive of a technology

00:44:52.610 --> 00:44:56.180
it is with things like
prerecorded ad breaks

00:44:56.180 --> 00:44:58.820
and I don't know what type of
listener attribution statistics

00:44:58.820 --> 00:45:00.783
you're able to get
and things like that.

00:45:00.783 --> 00:45:01.366
PJ VOGT: None.

00:45:01.366 --> 00:45:03.265
ALEX GOLDMAN: Not true.

00:45:03.265 --> 00:45:04.140
PJ VOGT: Very little.

00:45:04.140 --> 00:45:04.976
AUDIENCE: You know, like,
aside from the number

00:45:04.976 --> 00:45:06.770
of subscribers on iTunes.

00:45:06.770 --> 00:45:11.180
And so I love podcasts
because I love the content.

00:45:11.180 --> 00:45:15.800
And I've at times wondered,
is the primitive technology

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:20.900
holding back content
producers from maximizing

00:45:20.900 --> 00:45:23.390
their revenue streams in
a way that might threaten

00:45:23.390 --> 00:45:25.052
this thing that I really enjoy?

00:45:25.052 --> 00:45:26.510
ALEX GOLDMAN: It's
shuffling along.

00:45:26.510 --> 00:45:29.370
It's getting better.

00:45:29.370 --> 00:45:31.550
We dynamically insert
the ads in our show now.

00:45:31.550 --> 00:45:33.470
So you can yank them out.

00:45:33.470 --> 00:45:36.410
We can resell ads
on our back catalog.

00:45:36.410 --> 00:45:38.990
We have that
capability, which is

00:45:38.990 --> 00:45:43.700
huge in terms of monetization.

00:45:43.700 --> 00:45:50.510
With respect to being able
to chart our listeners,

00:45:50.510 --> 00:45:55.010
right now it's like our ratings
are probably about as accurate

00:45:55.010 --> 00:45:55.814
as Nielsen ratings.

00:45:55.814 --> 00:45:57.230
Not like we have
Nielsen families,

00:45:57.230 --> 00:46:00.430
but we know who downloads it.

00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:03.020
Or we know when it is
streamed to someone.

00:46:03.020 --> 00:46:05.870
So we get a number of people
who have downloaded it,

00:46:05.870 --> 00:46:08.930
downloaded and streamed it, and
that's total downloads for us.

00:46:08.930 --> 00:46:10.580
We don't know--

00:46:10.580 --> 00:46:13.410
I mean, we also are on
Spotify, which has an actual--

00:46:13.410 --> 00:46:15.290
which has pretty
detailed information

00:46:15.290 --> 00:46:18.200
about when people start
listening and stop listening.

00:46:18.200 --> 00:46:21.000
But other than that, we
don't have that information.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:23.580
However, I am told that
in the next couple weeks,

00:46:23.580 --> 00:46:29.510
we will be able to tell if
anyone is listening on iTunes,

00:46:29.510 --> 00:46:31.250
at what point do
they stop listening,

00:46:31.250 --> 00:46:34.012
which is very exciting.

00:46:34.012 --> 00:46:36.470
But if people are only listening
for the first four or five

00:46:36.470 --> 00:46:39.990
minutes, that's
kind of terrifying.

00:46:39.990 --> 00:46:45.350
But yeah, I think that slowly,
the technology is catching up.

00:46:45.350 --> 00:46:48.230
I don't know what that means
for the future of RSS feeds

00:46:48.230 --> 00:46:52.950
and things like that,
but slow, very slowly.

00:46:52.950 --> 00:46:55.450
I think mostly since "Serial"
blew up, people were like,

00:46:55.450 --> 00:46:56.450
oh, there's market here.

00:46:56.450 --> 00:46:58.800
Should probably figure out
ways to better monetize this.

00:46:58.800 --> 00:47:01.130
And once that happens,
dynamic ad insertion and stuff

00:47:01.130 --> 00:47:02.300
like that started happening.

00:47:02.300 --> 00:47:05.415
So slowly but surely.

00:47:05.415 --> 00:47:07.040
Part of what's nice
about them, though,

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:11.270
is that they are just these
files that once you get them

00:47:11.270 --> 00:47:13.417
on your phone, they're
yours, and you can fast

00:47:13.417 --> 00:47:15.500
forward and stop and pick
it up wherever you want.

00:47:15.500 --> 00:47:16.520
AUDIENCE: Works on the subway.

00:47:16.520 --> 00:47:17.353
ALEX GOLDMAN: Right.

00:47:17.353 --> 00:47:18.530
Exactly.

00:47:18.530 --> 00:47:24.710
So there is something to be said
for the primitiveness of them.

00:47:24.710 --> 00:47:28.460
SPEAKER 1: In terms of the
development of monetization,

00:47:28.460 --> 00:47:29.960
but also the
information that you're

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:31.850
able to get about
your listeners,

00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:36.830
to what extent does that bridge
the divide between podcasts

00:47:36.830 --> 00:47:38.810
that are either coming
out of big public radio

00:47:38.810 --> 00:47:41.840
organizations or
big podcast networks

00:47:41.840 --> 00:47:44.120
versus independent podcasters?

00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:46.130
Because one of the great
things about podcasting

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:48.080
is that you just
need a microphone

00:47:48.080 --> 00:47:50.660
and a tiny bit of hosting,
and you can have one.

00:47:50.660 --> 00:47:53.330
But there's also
these big institutions

00:47:53.330 --> 00:47:54.880
that continue to grow.

00:47:54.880 --> 00:47:55.880
PJ VOGT: I don't think--

00:47:55.880 --> 00:47:57.421
as far as I can
tell, there's nothing

00:47:57.421 --> 00:48:02.030
about the incremental
stuff going forward

00:48:02.030 --> 00:48:05.180
that should make that
divide bigger or change it.

00:48:05.180 --> 00:48:08.070
I think everybody--
basically, it

00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:12.470
amounts to big distributors
having better analytics.

00:48:12.470 --> 00:48:14.001
Everybody should have that.

00:48:14.001 --> 00:48:15.500
I do, though--
there's a part of me,

00:48:15.500 --> 00:48:16.640
and maybe it's
just superstitious,

00:48:16.640 --> 00:48:19.181
that thinks that the fact that
it's primitive is good for it,

00:48:19.181 --> 00:48:22.500
that somehow, I don't know what
I think is going to happen,

00:48:22.500 --> 00:48:25.250
but sometimes automation
is bad for content.

00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:28.970
Like, standardized
banner ads haven't

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:31.205
been great for writing
on the internet.

00:48:31.205 --> 00:48:32.955
It's probably just me
being superstitious.

00:48:32.955 --> 00:48:34.160
It's good right now.

00:48:34.160 --> 00:48:36.355
And so I'm waiting
for it to get bad.

00:48:36.355 --> 00:48:38.480
And every change, I'm like,
this is going to be it.

00:48:38.480 --> 00:48:40.040
This is going to
ruin everything.

00:48:40.040 --> 00:48:41.831
It's probably not going
to ruin everything.

00:48:41.831 --> 00:48:43.076
ALEX GOLDMAN: I have no idea.

00:48:43.076 --> 00:48:46.519
SPEAKER 1: Fair enough.

00:48:46.519 --> 00:48:47.060
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:48.810
I had a question
about, you've said

00:48:48.810 --> 00:48:52.340
that you have a lot of
stories in various stages

00:48:52.340 --> 00:48:54.200
kind of on the shelf
waiting to be revisited

00:48:54.200 --> 00:48:56.150
or being worked on
at the same time.

00:48:56.150 --> 00:48:57.630
I was wondering,
what's that kind

00:48:57.630 --> 00:49:02.150
of trigger that, OK, this
is ready to get in a slate,

00:49:02.150 --> 00:49:04.490
this is ready to
go on the schedule?

00:49:04.490 --> 00:49:08.600
And also, have you bumped things
in order to get something out

00:49:08.600 --> 00:49:09.880
in a timely way?

00:49:09.880 --> 00:49:12.810
I'm thinking about
the Pepe the Frog.

00:49:12.810 --> 00:49:13.620
PJ VOGT: Yeah.

00:49:13.620 --> 00:49:14.247
Yeah, we have.

00:49:14.247 --> 00:49:16.580
I mean, the trigger, oftentimes,
really, is desperation.

00:49:16.580 --> 00:49:21.770
Like, that thing is at 60%,
but everything else is at zero.

00:49:21.770 --> 00:49:24.029
Sometimes it might mean--

00:49:24.029 --> 00:49:25.820
sometimes it's just
about getting a person.

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:27.200
Like, this will only be good--

00:49:27.200 --> 00:49:30.049
we talk about proximity
with our stories,

00:49:30.049 --> 00:49:31.340
which can mean a lot of things.

00:49:31.340 --> 00:49:33.542
But if you're talking about
an event that happened,

00:49:33.542 --> 00:49:35.000
do you have somebody
who was there,

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.250
or just somebody who talked
to somebody who was there?

00:49:37.250 --> 00:49:39.470
And sometimes you'll get
an extra proximal step,

00:49:39.470 --> 00:49:40.937
which helps.

00:49:40.937 --> 00:49:43.520
Sometimes it might just be that
you didn't know what it meant,

00:49:43.520 --> 00:49:46.970
and now you feel like you have
an idea about the question

00:49:46.970 --> 00:49:49.270
you're actually asking,
or the conclusion you

00:49:49.270 --> 00:49:50.140
think you've got.

00:49:50.140 --> 00:49:52.940
Sometimes they're
just brain changes.

00:49:52.940 --> 00:49:55.730
ALEX GOLDMAN: Or Tim,
who PJ previously

00:49:55.730 --> 00:50:00.470
described as a genius, will
be like, what if we try x?

00:50:00.470 --> 00:50:02.690
What if instead of
interviewing this person,

00:50:02.690 --> 00:50:04.990
what if you talked to this
person about their dog?

00:50:04.990 --> 00:50:06.698
PJ VOGT: Or like with
Sruthi, Sruthi just

00:50:06.698 --> 00:50:09.024
did this story a few weeks ago.

00:50:09.024 --> 00:50:10.190
ALEX GOLDMAN: The ALS story?

00:50:10.190 --> 00:50:11.565
PJ VOGT: Yeah,
the first one, she

00:50:11.565 --> 00:50:17.000
was profiling this guy who had a
really different way of looking

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:18.380
for an ALS cure.

00:50:18.380 --> 00:50:21.470
And the story was like, it
was in that sort of like,

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:23.720
almost ready to
go, but something--

00:50:23.720 --> 00:50:25.640
we thought it was
something was missing.

00:50:25.640 --> 00:50:30.044
And then we had an
edit, and I suggested,

00:50:30.044 --> 00:50:32.210
I was like, I think we're
making it too complicated.

00:50:32.210 --> 00:50:34.751
Like, there was a version of
the story that was sort of like,

00:50:34.751 --> 00:50:37.310
is what he's doing
right or wrong?

00:50:37.310 --> 00:50:39.470
Because he was
working with patients

00:50:39.470 --> 00:50:42.072
and checking out
their obscure cure

00:50:42.072 --> 00:50:43.280
to see if they could be good.

00:50:43.280 --> 00:50:45.080
And we were having this
whole moral dilemma.

00:50:45.080 --> 00:50:47.000
But everybody in the room
on the editorial staff

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:48.124
was like, we like this guy.

00:50:48.124 --> 00:50:50.180
It doesn't seem--
we can't credibly

00:50:50.180 --> 00:50:52.010
make the other side
of this argument.

00:50:52.010 --> 00:50:53.480
And realizing we didn't
care about the argument

00:50:53.480 --> 00:50:55.330
we were telling, and
realizing, oh, it's

00:50:55.330 --> 00:50:57.110
just a story about this guy.

00:50:57.110 --> 00:50:58.544
We had the story about the guy.

00:50:58.544 --> 00:50:59.960
We had been having
trouble finding

00:50:59.960 --> 00:51:01.709
someone who could be
a good critic of him,

00:51:01.709 --> 00:51:03.750
because they didn't exist.

00:51:03.750 --> 00:51:05.530
So sometimes it's
simplifying, and Tim

00:51:05.530 --> 00:51:06.990
is really good at
being like, you

00:51:06.990 --> 00:51:08.950
think your story is
these seven things.

00:51:08.950 --> 00:51:09.620
It's that thing.

00:51:09.620 --> 00:51:11.960
Just take the interesting
part and get out of here.

00:51:11.960 --> 00:51:13.751
ALEX GOLDMAN: And that
story was originally

00:51:13.751 --> 00:51:15.290
going to run the
week that we ran

00:51:15.290 --> 00:51:17.870
that episode about Pizzagate,
because Pizzagate just

00:51:17.870 --> 00:51:20.040
became a thing.

00:51:20.040 --> 00:51:21.912
So I was like-- and
Sruthi was like,

00:51:21.912 --> 00:51:23.120
I'm having trouble with this.

00:51:23.120 --> 00:51:24.719
I'm really grappling
with this story.

00:51:24.719 --> 00:51:26.010
Can you come up with something?

00:51:26.010 --> 00:51:27.410
And I was like, eh.

00:51:27.410 --> 00:51:31.340
And then we did that "Yes Yes
No" about Pizzagate, and then

00:51:31.340 --> 00:51:33.680
the following day, a huge--

00:51:33.680 --> 00:51:36.230
we were like, that will be
the first half of the show.

00:51:36.230 --> 00:51:38.630
And then the following day,
just that crazy explosion

00:51:38.630 --> 00:51:41.960
took place, and, well,
when I say crazy explosion,

00:51:41.960 --> 00:51:44.280
I mean a guy walked into
the pizza place with a gun.

00:51:44.280 --> 00:51:46.155
So a guy walked into a
pizza place with a gun

00:51:46.155 --> 00:51:48.930
and suddenly it was
like an entire episode.

00:51:48.930 --> 00:51:50.900
So yes, things
move around a lot.

00:51:50.900 --> 00:51:53.150
SPEAKER 1: We've got time
for one more quick question.

00:51:53.150 --> 00:51:53.460
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:51:53.460 --> 00:51:54.635
It's a tough one.

00:51:54.635 --> 00:51:55.830
No, I'm just kidding.

00:51:55.830 --> 00:51:58.322
What's with all the
love for Matt Lieber?

00:51:58.322 --> 00:51:59.030
PJ VOGT: Oh, man.

00:52:01.880 --> 00:52:04.710
He's just particularly
when Gimlet started,

00:52:04.710 --> 00:52:07.937
it was like, he was
the only person who

00:52:07.937 --> 00:52:09.020
had any understanding of--

00:52:12.828 --> 00:52:14.870
he does so many things
that are so good,

00:52:14.870 --> 00:52:16.220
and they're so hard to describe.

00:52:16.220 --> 00:52:17.850
And so that's where
that comes from.

00:52:17.850 --> 00:52:20.990
But he's just a
grown-up who makes sure

00:52:20.990 --> 00:52:23.860
that everything is
going to be OK tomorrow,

00:52:23.860 --> 00:52:25.590
and there's going
to be a budget,

00:52:25.590 --> 00:52:28.770
and nothing is
going to disappear.

00:52:28.770 --> 00:52:31.410
ALEX GOLDMAN: Well, also, when
